SIMPLE: prudential
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prudential
<hw>Pru*den"tial</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Proceeding from, or dictated or characterized by, prudence;
prudent; discreet; sometimes, selfish or pecuniary as distinguished from
higher motives or influences; <as>as, <ex>prudential</ex>
motives</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ A <xex>prudential</xex> line of
conduct.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exercising prudence; discretionary; advisory;
superintending or executive; <as>as, a <ex>prudential</ex>
committee</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prudential</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prudential
<hw>Pru*den"tial</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which relates to or
demands the exercise of, discretion or prudence; -- usually in the
<pluf>pl.</pluf></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many stanzas, in poetic measures, contain rules relating to common
<qex>prudentials</qex> as well as to religion.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prudentialist</ent>⟦br⟧
